body:
Discussing @mikeurbach's points [in the last PR](https://github.com/llvm/circt/pull/1301#pullrequestreview-691094464), it seems that there are two current approaches to modeling a module-type op in MLIR currently. Right now, I’ve followed the `HW` approach: treat the ComponentOp like a function with arguments and results. E.g.
```
calyx.component @MyComponent(%in1) -> (%out1) { ... }
```

This means we’d also have to define a component cell (instance) in the following manner (pseudo-IR):
```
%c0.out1 = calyx.cell "c0" @MyComponent(%some_input)
```

However, within Calyx world, we are only declaring instances thus no connections are made until wires and control.
E.g.
```
component myComp(in1: 32) -> (out1: 32) { ... }

component main() -> () {
  cells {
    myComp = MyComp();
  }
  wires {
  }
  control {
    invoke myComp(in1 = 1'd1)(out1 = someValue);
  }
}
```

It feels kind of bad to lose the FunctionLike interface, given how closely a Component is to a function. Ideally we'd like to lazily make these connections after instantiation. Perhaps this means just using a non-FunctionLike interface and `Connect`s as modeled in `FIRRTL`/`LLHD` (and the Calyx language itself) is better.
